│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The core of the issue is a crash in `getSpillCost` because `SpillPlacementBB` is null. This happens when the vectorizer determines it must spill a value (`MustSpill` is true), but it   │
│ cannot find a valid basic block to place the spill (`getSpillPlacementBlock` returns null). This scenario occurs with the provided reproducer because one of the values to be spilled is │
│ a function argument, which has no parent basic block.                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ My previous attempts to fix this have either been too aggressive, causing widespread test regressions by preventing valid vectorizations, or have been subtly incorrect. The regressions │
│ indicate that simply invalidating the vectorization candidate or returning a zero cost when a spill location isn't found is not the right approach. The cost model is delicate, and      │
│ these changes alter its behavior for valid code.                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The most direct and least disruptive fix is to make `getSpillCost` itself robust to a null `SpillPlacementBB`. If `SpillPlacementBB` is null, it means no spill can be inserted. In this │
│ case, the cost of spilling is effectively infinite, as the action is impossible. Returning a very high cost from `getSpillCost` will signal to the vectorizer that this specific path is │
│ prohibitively expensive, without outright invalidating the entire vectorization analysis. This allows the vectorizer's cost model to function as intended, exploring other possibilities │
│ that might not involve this impossible spill. This approach should prevent the crash while minimizing the impact on the existing logic and avoiding test regressions.                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will modify `getSpillCost` to check if `SpillPlacementBB` is null. If it is, the function will return `InstructionCost::getInf()`, representing an infinite cost.                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '/BasicBlock \*BB = SpillPlacementBB;/a \  if (!BB)\n    return InstructionCost::getInf();' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                       │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
